406→                           A question of Roth, Erdős, Sárközy, and Sós <a href="#cite-ESS89-439" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ESS89','439'); return false;">[ESS89]</a> (according to some reports, although in <a href="#cite-Er80c-439" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er80c','439'); return false;">[Er80c]</a> Erdős claims this arose in a conversation with Silverman in 1977). Erdős, Sárközy, and Sós <a href="#cite-ESS89-439" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ESS89','439'); return false;">[ESS89]</a> proved this for $2$ or $3$ colours.<br><br> In other words, if $G$ is the infinite graph on $\mathbb{N}$ where we connect $m,n$ by an edge if and only if $n+m$ is a square, then is the chromatic number of $G$ equal to $\aleph_0$?<br><br>This is true, as proved by Khalfalah and Szemerédi <a href="#cite-KhSz06-439" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('KhSz06','439'); return false;">[KhSz06]</a>, who in fact prove the general result with $x+y=z^2$ replaced by $x+y=f(z)$ for any non-constant $f(z)\in \mathbb{Z}[z]$ such that $2\mid f(z)$ for some $z\in \mathbb{Z}$. <br><br>See also <a href="/438" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[438]</a>.
